# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] The **Alliance for Direct Democracy in Europe**, abbreviated to **ADDE**, was a European political party founded in 2014.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] It was composed of parties belonging to the Europe of Freedom and Direct Democracy (EFDD) group in the European Parliament (EP).
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] The dominant national party in the ADDE was the UK Independence Party (UKIP), providing 21 of the party's 27 members of the European Parliament (MEPs) elected in 2014.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] A further three UKIP MEPs chose not to participate in the ADDE.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] In 2015, the ADDE was recognised by the European Parliament and its grant maximum from the EP was set at €1,241,725, with an additional €730,053 for its affiliated political foundation, the *Initiative for Direct Democracy*.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] ADDE was closed down in 2016 after an auditors' inquiry found misspending of EU funds.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] The party was legally dissolved on 24 May 2017.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] The **Alliance for Europe of the Nations** was a European political party that gathered conservative and national-conservative political parties from across the continent.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] The AEN was founded in 2002, designed to complement the existing Union for Europe of the Nations group in the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] Moves towards establishing standardised funding block grants for European political parties were at this point well afoot, and the parties affiliated with UEN required a corresponding organisation to take advantage of them.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] Almost immediately upon its founding, the AEN began to decline in terms of membership and influence.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] At its first meeting, participants included the Czech Civic Democratic Party, Portuguese CDS-PP, Israeli Likud, Irish Fianna Fáil, Italian National Alliance and the Greek Popular Orthodox Rally, all of which later left the organisation.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] The AEN had a broadly national-conservative political line, but many members were uncomfortable with this.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] There was a strong movement for the centrist Fianna Fáil to leave AEN and join the European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party, which it did on 17 April 2009.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] After those realignments, there were too few AEN member parties left to retain its EU-funded status as a European political party.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The **Alliance for Peace and Freedom** (**APF**) is a far-right European political alliance and former European political party founded on 4 February 2015.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The main member parties were involved in the defunct **European National Front**.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The alliance wishes to establish a network of nationalist movements across Europe that will cooperate to strengthen their shared ideals.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] It cooperates and supports other nationalist groups across Europe that are not members, these include former party members Golden Dawn, Tricolour Flame, Alternative for Sweden and the ELAM.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The alliance is described as neo-Nazi by several newspapers, and neo-fascist by others.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The group works for "a Europe of sovereign nations in which the independent states work together on a confederated basis", and for the perennity and the safeguarding of ancestral European traditions such as the Christian tradition.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The Europa Terra Nostra is the official European political foundation of the APF.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The ETN was founded 3 July 2015 in Berlin where it continues to operate as the official think-tank of the APF and serves as the European framework for national foundations/think-tanks recognised by APF member-parties.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The APF works to co-ordinate European nationalist parties across the continent.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] It helped establish the Italy for the Italians coalition composed of APF member New Force along with Tricolour Flame.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] In 2017 the APF aided in the formation of the National Identity Bloc in Europe coalition, APF members, United Romania Party and Noua Dreaptă joined forces with the Greater Romania Party.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] In 2019 The APF played a part in forming the ADÑ Identidad Española coalition, composed of APF member National Democracy, FE-JONS, Spanish Alternative and La Falange.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The party also maintains contacts with the former leader of the National Front, Jean-Marie Le Pen, who was expelled from his party in 2015.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] He joined the group in March 2018 as an Honorary Chairman and held this position until his death in January 2025.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The APF maintains contacts with conservative circles in Russia with the group being invited to conferences hosted by the Kremlin.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The party supports Vladimir Putin and United Russia's leadership of Russia, especially in the Russo-Ukrainian War and Syrian Civil War.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The party is supportive of Alexander Lukashenko and maintains contacts with the Liberal Democratic Party of Belarus.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The APF strongly supports Serbian nationalists and is opposed to international recognition of Kosovo, it has worked in the past with the Serbian Radical Party.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] On 26 September 2021, the APF held a conference in Belgrade hosted by the Serbian Right.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] It maintained friendly relations with the Syrian Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party government with deputy chairman, Nick Griffin being invited to Syria by Bashar al-Assad multiple times as an ambassador.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] Meetings between the party and the Syrian Social Nationalist Party have been held with the AFP publicly supporting the SSNP.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The group maintains contacts with Hezbollah and has hosted at least one meeting with Hezbollah leaders.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] Michel Aoun, then president of Lebanon, received a delegation of the APF in 2018 and in 2019, and the group claims to have been in regular contact with him and his party.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] The **Alliance of European National Movements** (**AENM**) was a European political party that was formed in Budapest on 24 October 2009 by a number of ultranationalist and far-right parties from countries in Europe.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] AENM's founding members were Jobbik (the alliance was established during their sixth party congress), France's National Front, Italy's Tricolour Flame, Sweden's National Democrats and Belgium's National Front.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At the end of 2011, the National Front withdrew from AENM and joined the European Alliance for Freedom (EAF).
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2014, the All-Ukrainian Union "Freedom" terminated its observer status in the AENM, due to many members of the bloc showing support for Russia in the Russo-Ukrainian war.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In February 2016, Jobbik cut all of its affiliation with AENM, and the president of AENM Béla Kovács left Jobbik.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In November 2009, the British National Party claimed that AENM had been extended to nine parties, but this information was not confirmed by AENM President Bruno Gollnisch in 2012.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At a press conference held in Strasbourg on 16 June 2010, the political leadership of AENM was confirmed as follows: President Bruno Gollnisch, Vice President Nick Griffin, Treasurer Béla Kovács and Secretary General Valerio Cignetti.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At the end of 2011 the National Front withdrew from AENM and joined the European Alliance for Freedom.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] However, Gollnisch and Jean-Marie Le Pen maintained their position in the organisation.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In October 2013, Marine Le Pen requested that Gollnisch and Jean-Marie Le Pen leave their positions in the AENM in order to join the more moderate EAF and so unify the French National Front under the EAF banner.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Marine Le Pen has tried to "de-demonize" the party, i.e. to give it a more acceptable image.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Cooperation with the openly racist and antisemitic parties present in AENM was seen as contradictory to these aims.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] On November 7, the two declared they have followed the request and left AENM.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] This also meant the end of Gollnisch's term as the AENM's chairman, a place occupied by Béla Kovács since January 2014.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In the spring of 2013, Svoboda lost its observer status after a conflict with other member groups over its policies towards ethnic minorities in the West of Ukraine.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Béla Kovács, leader of the alliance, had served as an observer at the 2014 Donbass parliamentary election.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2014, there were accusations against Chairman Kovács that he or his wife were working for the Russian intelligence service.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2015 the European Parliament lifted Kovács immunity.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In September 2020, he was cleared of the charge of espionage.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] However, he had worked with the Russian secret service SVR RF, but mostly in the form of influencing, with the aim to promote Russian interests through the AEMN.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Kovács was sentenced to one and a half years imprisonment for fraud and falsification of documents to the detriment of the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] The party did not apply for registration with the newly established Authority for European Political Parties and European Political Foundations (APPF), which was required from 2017, in good time.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] An application by the party foundation ITE was rejected by the APPF, as the AEMN was not registered itself at that time.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Subsequently, the AEMN's application for funding for 2018 was rejected accordingly.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Finally, the AEMN was registered as a European political party on 12 January 2018.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At the end of 2018, the AENM was removed from the register again.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] The background was a change in the registration rules, according to which European parties had to submit member parties (with parliamentarians) from seven EU member states in the register.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] This put an end to the previous practice of AENM registering individual parliamentarians from national parties who did not belong to AENM but to other European parties.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] For example, parliamentarians from the Front National had regularly provided signatures for the AENM, the APF and the MENL – to which the FN belongs.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] For the 2019 European Parliament election, AEMN chairman Kovacs provided the necessary signature of support for the candidacy of the Italian party CasaPound Italia.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] None of the parties in the AEMN's environment was able to win mandates in the election.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] After the election, the party was no longer active.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] For the 2024 European Parliament election in Italy, Royal Italy submitted a symbol with the text "Alleanza europea dei movimenti nazionali" at the top.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2022, Royal Italy ran with United Right who made a deal with CasaPound in 2019.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] The **Alliance of Independent Democrats in Europe** (AIDE) (**Alliance des Démocrates Indépendants en Europe** (ADIE) in French) was a Eurosceptic, nationalist European political party.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] AIDE was created on 28 October 2005 in the Rhône prefecture.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] AIDE described itself as the centre-right faction of the eurosceptic IND/DEM group, with the EUDemocrats, the United Kingdom Independence Party and the European Christian Political Movement comprising the other factions of that group.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] As of January 2007, the group operated a limited French-language website.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] The group's website implied the existence of British, Czech, French, Greek, Irish, Italian and Polish delegations and identified Movement for France (MpF) MEP Patrick Louis as the president of AIDE.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] AIDE was dissolved with effect from 31 December 2008 and was defunded in the February 2009 meeting of the Bureau of the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The Mission of the ALDE-PACE group is to promote core values of the Council of Europe: democracy, human rights and the rule of law through enhanced political actions inside and outside the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] ALDE adopted a new mission statement 22 January 2018 outlining the values and objectives of the group.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] ALDE members realize these objectives by actively participating in the Parliamentary Assembly sessions, working in its Committees, drafting reports, initiating debates and ensuring the follow-up of this work in their home countries.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] Outside the Assembly the group members are committed to promoting the principles of the Council of Europe and giving support to liberal and democratic values throughout Europe.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] According to the Rules of Procedure of the ALDE-PACE (as amended on 22 January 2018), the Bureau of the Group consists of the Chairperson, 11 Vice-Chairpersons and the Treasurer of the Group.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] Chairpersons of committees and former Chairpersons of the Group are ex officio members of the Bureau.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The permanent secretariat of the Group is located in the headquarters of the Council of Europe in Strasbourg, France (Palais de l’Europe).
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The secretariat is chaired by Dr Maria Bigday.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] It was not until after the celebration of the Council of Europe's 25th anniversary in 1964 that the Rules of Procedure of the Consultative Assembly (its name was not changed to Parliamentary Assembly until 1974) discreetly mentioned that members had the possibility of forming political groups.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The history of the liberal group in the PACE dates back to the early 1970s (first documented in 1974).
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] At the time it was called the Liberal Group and consisted of 30 members headed by Frederik Portheine (Netherlands).
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] In the mid-80s the group changed its name to the "Liberal, Democratic and Reformers' Group" (LDR) in order to make the Group's political ideals universally and unequivocally recognisable.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The name "Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe" (ALDE) was adopted on 20 June 2005 in order to enhance cooperation with other European liberal and democratic bodies, in particular the ALDE of the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] Daniel Tarschys (Sweden) was Secretary General of the Council of Europe from 1994 - 1999.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The permanent secretariat of the Group operates since 1978, when Mr Peter Kallenberger was appointed Secretary of the Group.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] After he retired in 2010, Ms Maria Bigday took up the position of the Secretary.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The ALDE-PACE Group regularly holds conferences, hearings, seminars and round tables in the framework of the Council of Europe scope of interest.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] It also co-organises joint events with other European and international liberal and democratic institutions.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] Information relating to these side events is found on the ALDE-PACE Pace website and in the ALDE newsletter published after each session.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The ALDE-PACE holds stable partnership with major European and world liberal and democratic organisations.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The **Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party** (**ALDE Party**) is a liberal European political party composed of national parties from across Europe, mainly active in the European Union.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The ALDE Party is affiliated with Liberal International and a recognised European political party, incorporated as a non-profit association under Belgian law.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] It was founded on 26 March 1976 in Stuttgart as a confederation of national political parties under the name "Federation of Liberal and Democrat Parties in Europe" and renamed "European Liberals and Democrats" (ELD) in 1977 and "European Liberal Democrats and Reformists" (ELDR) in 1986.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 30 April 2004, the ELDR was reformed as an official European party, the "European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party" (ELDR Party).
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Prior to the 2004 European election, the European party had been represented through its own group, the European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party Group (ELDR) Group.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In June 2019, the ALDE group was succeeded by Renew Europe.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of 2024, ALDE Party is represented in European Union institutions, with 51 MEPs and five members of the European Commission.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Of the 27 EU member states, there are two with ALDE-affiliated Prime Ministers: Kristen Michal (Estonian Reform Party) in Estonia and Alexander De Croo (Open VLD) in Belgium.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE Party members are also in governments in ten other EU member states: Cyprus, France, Denmark, Finland, Sweden, Ireland, Luxembourg, Lithuania, Germany and the Netherlands.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Charles Michel, former Belgian prime minister, was the president of the European Council until December 2024.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE's think tank is the European Liberal Forum, led by Jan-Christoph Oetjen MEP, and gathers 46 member organisations.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The youth wing of ALDE is the European Liberal Youth (LYMEC), which is predominantly based upon youth and student liberal organisations but contains also a small number of individual members.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 2011, ALDE Party became the first pan-European party to create the status of individual membership.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Since then, between 1000 and close to 3000 members (the numbers fluctuate annually) maintained direct membership in the ALDE Party from several EU countries.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Over 40 coordinators mobilised liberal ideas, initiatives and expertise across the continent under the leadership of the steering committee, which was first chaired by Julie Cantalou.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The ALDE Party took a step further in the direction of becoming a truly pan-European party when granting voting rights to individual members' delegates at the Party Congress.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Individual membership was eventually discontinued in 2023.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 2025, the Alliance was declared an undesirable organization in Russia.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Pan-European liberalism has a long history dating back to the foundation of Liberal International in April 1947.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 26 March 1976, the Federation of Liberal and Democrat Parties in Europe was established in Stuttgart.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The founding parties of the federation were the Free Democratic Party of Germany, Radical Party of France, Venstre of Denmark, Italian Liberal Party, Dutch People's Party for Freedom and Democracy and Democratic Party of Luxembourg.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Observer members joining later in 1976 were the Danish Social Liberal Party, French Radical Party of the Left and Independent Republicans, British Liberal Party, and Italian Republican Party.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 1977, the federation was renamed European Liberals and Democrats, in 1986, European Liberal Democrats and Reformists.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 10 November 2012, the ELDR Party adopted the name of the alliance between the two parties, to match the parliamentary group and the alliance.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 12 June 2019, the ALDE group was succeeded by a new enlarged group, Renew Europe, which primarily consists of ALDE and EDP member parties and France's La République En Marche!
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As a registered European political party, ALDE is entitled to European public funding, which it has received continuously since 2004.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of European public funding received by ALDE.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In line with the Regulation on European political parties and European political foundations, ALDE also raises private funds to co-finance its activities.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of 2025, European parties must raise at least 10% of their reimbursable expenditure from private sources, while the rest can be covered using European public funding.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of contributions and donations received by the ALDE.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of January 2026 ALDE party had 55 full member and ten affiliated parties from EU and non-EU countries.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Only delegates from full members of the ALDE Party and its youth wing LYMEC, together with the delegates of the ALDE Party Supporters and ALDE Party Bureau members, are permitted to vote at the ALDE Congress and Council.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Affiliated member parties have non-voting delegates.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE also includes a number of individual members.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] For many years, ALDE had the largest number of individual members of all European parties; however, this membership was discontinued with only one individual member remaining as of 2024.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As most other European parties, it has not sought to develop mass individual membership.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of individual membership of ALDE since 2019.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/animal-politics-eu] Animal Politics EU is considered left-wing.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/animal-politics-eu] The parties of Animal Politics EU take clear left-wing ideological positions, calling for enlargements of welfare systems, stressing the need to fight against social inequalities, and openly criticizing capitalism.
[src:alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe/animal-politics-eu] All parties of Animal Politics EU also share a rejection of speciesism, arguing that it is morally unjustifiable to exclude non-human animals and their suffering from moral considerations.
